undance differences, enabling relative comparison of fold-changes across all metabolites.\"\n },\n {\n \"action\": \"Save the preprocessed matrix as CSV to tmp/preprocessed_expression_matrix.csv with molecule names as the first column and sample IDs as headers. Generate a preprocessing summary report (tmp/preprocessing_report.txt) documenting: number of molecules and samples, number of imputed values, column sum normalization factor per sample, log-transform decision (not applied), and median scaling confirmation.\",\n \"goal\": \"Persist the preprocessed data for downstream analysis and document the preprocessing steps for reproducibility.\"\n }\n ],\n \"notes\": \"1. DATA TYPE: This is untargeted metabolomics LC-MS data (2059 metabolites). The expression values range ~0.1 to ~5.8, which is relatively narrow. The standard preprocessing pipeline will be applied to ensure consistency.\\n\\n2. QC SAMPLES: Three QC samples (Fc16YH_QC01-03) are listed in sampleinfo.csv but do NOT appear in the expression matrix columns \u2014 they are excluded.\\n\\n3. SAMPLE GROUPS:\\n - 'high iron diet before' (FE1-FE6): High-iron diet + CDI infection (experimental)\\n - 'Clostridium difficile infection' (CD1-CD6): CDI infection only (disease control)\\n - 'Standard (control)' (NC1-NC6): Healthy, no infection (baseline control)\\n\\n4. LOG TRANSFORMATION SKIPPED: Raw max value (~5.8) <<100, indicating the data is already on a linear scale.\\n\\n5. MOLECULE ANNOTATION: A complementary file (G:/OmicsWorks/test/metabolism/metabolites.csv) with2172 entries and32 annotation columns is available for downstream biological interpretation.\\n\\n6. RESEARCH CONTEXT: Preprocessed data will be used to compare metabolite abundance across groups to identify metabolites mediating the protective effect of high-iron diet against CDI, particularly L-proline, TUDCA, bile acids, and SCFAs as described in the research background.\"\n}\n```"
